✅ STEP 1 — OPEN TERMINAL
Open Mac terminal.

✅ STEP 2 — GO TO DOWNLOADS FOLDER
(Where PEM files are stored)
cd Downloads

✅ STEP 3 — FIX KP1.pem PERMISSIONS
chmod 400 KP1.pem

🎯 WHY?
AWS requires private key permissions to be restricted.
Without this: ❌ SSH login fails.

✅ STEP 4 — CONNECT TO VM1
ssh -i KP1.pem ubuntu@3.25.153.90

🧠 UNDERSTAND THIS COMMAND
Part	Meaning
ssh	Secure Shell login
-i KP1.pem	use private key
ubuntu	AWS Ubuntu username
3.25.153.90	VM1 public IP
⚠️ FIRST TIME CONNECTION
You may see:
Are you sure you want to continue connecting?
Type:
yes

🎉 SUCCESS
Terminal changes to:
ubuntu@ip-172-31-xx-xx
Meaning: ✅ connected to VM1.

✅ STEP 5 — CREATE FILE IN VM1
Inside VM1 run:
touch test.txt

✅ STEP 6 — ADD CONTENT TO FILE
Open file:
nano test.txt
Add:
Hello Cloud Computing

✅ SAVE FILE
Press:
* CTRL + O
* Enter
* CTRL + X

✅ STEP 7 — VERIFY FILE
Run:
ls
Expected:
test.txt

✅ STEP 8 — EXIT VM1
Run:
exit
Back to:
apple@MacBookPro

✅ STEP 9 — COPY KP2.pem INTO VM1
📍RUN ON MAC TERMINAL
scp -i KP1.pem KP2.pem ubuntu@3.25.153.90:/home/ubuntu

🎯 WHY THIS STEP?
VM1 needs:
KP2.pem
to authenticate into VM2.

✅ STEP 10 — LOGIN INTO VM1 AGAIN
ssh -i KP1.pem ubuntu@3.25.153.90

✅ STEP 11 — CHECK FILES
Inside VM1:
ls
Expected:
KP2.pem
test.txt

✅ STEP 12 — FIX KP2.pem PERMISSIONS
Inside VM1 run:
chmod 400 KP2.pem

🎯 WHY?
Without correct permissions: ❌ SCP/SSH authentication fails.

✅ STEP 13 — TRANSFER FILE TO VM2
Inside VM1 run:
scp -i KP2.pem test.txt ubuntu@13.239.249.62:/home/ubuntu

🧠 UNDERSTAND THIS COMMAND
Part	Meaning
scp	secure copy
-i KP2.pem	use VM2 key
test.txt	file to transfer
ubuntu	destination username
13.239.249.62	VM2 public IP
/home/ubuntu	destination path
⚠️ FIRST TIME CONNECTION
